the mind of the philosopher which has been strengthened and persected by virtue is superior to the assaults of evil (ef. iii 5, 11 ‘eos enim sanos quoniam intellegi necesse est, quorum mens motu quasi morbo perturbata nullo sit ’)‚ since evil can attack the soul only from within, but the body is always open to attacks of disease which come from without and from sources not under its control. et is Sff.'s correction of the MSS sed3 Madv. and Tregd. omit the words non possunt, corpora and credit Cicero with the incon— sistent statement that the philosophie mind is subject to mental disturbance. Bent. inserted ut before corpora. Sff. is evidently right in reading et: the state- ment in the second sentence is not a correction of, nor in contrast to, the statement in the first 2 it is the statement of the essential difference between mental and bodily morbi which is the justifica- tion for the statement in the first clause. Sed is retained by Heine (Posen Progr. p. 6) who regardsy it as marking a transi- tion from one idea to another.
